snippet.textDisplay: Zach: I also got diagnosed with OCD in Jr. High! (We didn't call it Middle School here) I remember that at that time, nobody knew what OCD was, so it was really hard because I remember I used to have to repeat things like "I think" under my breath every time I made a statement to someone, otherwise I just KNEW something bad was going to happen. My little niece noticed it during a family trip and asked me why I kept saying that, and I remember being sooo embarrassed for being called out. I also would develop urinary tract infections because if I didn't step in the EXACT "correct" spots on the floor on my way to my bedroom door in the morning, I would have to go back and lay down in my bed and start all over. So I would have to hold in my urine sometimes for hours because I couldn't make it out of my bedroom. It eventually got better, but other problems took its place. Now that I'm older, I feel a lot more relaxed and have the right medications. But it still does kind of hurt and anger me when people who don't actually have OCD say things like, "OMG, my OCD is so bad right now!" because of normal things like not wanting to touch something gross. People, be mindful of what you say, because unless you actually have OCD, Bipolar Disorder, ACTUAL migraines (not just bad headaches), etc, don't use them as descriptors. You have no idea what it's like to have to deal with these afflictions.

snippet.textDisplay:
Wait.... Zach opening up about OCD. We need more of it. I have OCD, I have arithmomania, obsessive thoughts as well as dealt with post partum OCD. Nobody talks about OCD and it’s stigmatized and joked about so much... can we please get a full video to bring light to the subject matter? Many of us who deal with it would be happy to have someone on a large platform speak of it.

To add, the OCD I have can flourish into really wonderful things. I’ve don’t photography since I was a freshman in high school (I’m 27... yes, old lol), and my OCD has helped me create my best photos. However, when I don’t have an outlet is when it becomes absolutely debilitating. It isn’t always just germs and having things neat. Sometimes it’s obsessive thoughts and fears that keep you from experiencing life. It’s hard to deal with, especially without medications, and it gets over looked so much.

snippet.textDisplay:
Since I was in 5th grade I had a bad time. In 10th and 11th grade, it was ok, because my old bullies were gone. I'm currently in 12th grade and I'm struggling with many anxieties. My biggest fear are silent rooms with people in it because I always get hungry in these situations and have to fear that my stomach is making noises.

I hate tests because whatever I try, no matter how much I eat during these super long tests I'm always hungry. That new problem exists since a month. My other problems started in September. And even if I already wasn't happy in the 11th grade, it's even worse now. I have so many fears...I also can only sit on one specific spot to be able to focus on the test.

And tomorrow is the next test, almost 3 hours and on Friday there will be an English test for almost 4 hours. And I still have 12 tests to go for the next two or 3 months. I just don't know how I'll survive that... It seems impossible to me. Every day I cry myself to sleep and I'd like to get some help in a clinic because my problems are taking over my life. But I would never ask my parents if they would help me by doing that.

Seriously, I have almost no friends and I usually don't leave the house. I miss my old life. And there's still a year to go for me until I'm finished with school.
I know everyone will say 'Wtf your problems aren't reap problems'
But you don't know me and my reality and what I've gone through the years before. I wish I was someone else.
